<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/6624> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #6624" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/3> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "A Lex Aebutia, probably tribunicial, barred the author of a law from holding an office established by it. This law precedes 63 (Cic. Leg. Agr. 2.21; Dom. 51), but may be after the Gracchi (see however Niccolini, FTP 411, on Liv. Per. 58). If Aebutius lived in the second century he may be the author of the law which introduced the formulary process (Gaius 4.30, FIRA 2.156; see Wenger, RE 6.2859)." .
